            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What are apparent and absolute magnitude?</h2>
              <p>
                Astronomers use the <strong>magnitude scale</strong> to describe
                how bright an object appears or truly is:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Apparent magnitude (m)</strong>: how bright an object
                  looks from Earth.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Absolute magnitude (M)</strong>: how bright it would
                  look if placed at a standard distance of
                  <strong>10 parsecs</strong> (about 32.6 light-years).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The scale is <strong>logarithmic and inverted</strong>: a
                smaller (or more negative) magnitude means a
                <strong>brighter</strong> object. A difference of 5 magnitudes
                corresponds to a factor of 100 in brightness.
              </p>

              <h2>Key formulas</h2>

              <h3>1. Distance modulus (linking m, M, and distance)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Standard form (distance in parsecs):</p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  m − M = 5 log<sub>10</sub>(d) − 5
                </p>
                <p>Rearranged:</p>
                <ul class="font-mono text-sm">
                  <li>M = m − 5 log<sub>10</sub>(d) + 5</li>
                  <li>m = M + 5 log<sub>10</sub>(d) − 5</li>
                  <li>d (pc) = 10<sup>(m − M + 5)/5</sup></li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Converting distance units</h3>
              <div class="formula-box font-mono text-sm">
                1 parsec ≈ 3.26156 light-years<br />
                d(pc) = d(ly) / 3.26156<br />
                d(ly) = d(pc) × 3.26156
              </div>

              <h3>3. Luminosity and absolute magnitude</h3>
              <p>
                Absolute magnitude is directly related to
                <strong>intrinsic luminosity</strong>. If M is the absolute
                magnitude of a star and M<sub>☉</sub> is the Sun’s absolute
                magnitude in the same band:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box font-mono text-sm">
                L / L<sub>☉</sub> = 10<sup>(M<sub>☉</sub> − M)/2.5</sup><br />
                M = M<sub>☉</sub> − 2.5 log<sub>10</sub>(L / L<sub>☉</sub>)
              </div>
              <p>
                A difference of 1 magnitude corresponds to a factor of about
                2.512 in luminosity:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box font-mono text-sm">
                2.512 ≈ 10<sup>0.4</sup>
              </div>

              <h2>Worked examples</h2>

              <h3>Example 1 – Absolute magnitude of Sirius</h3>
              <p>
                Sirius has apparent magnitude m ≈ −1.46 and distance d ≈ 2.64
                pc.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Compute log<sub>10</sub>(d): log<sub>10</sub>(2.64) ≈ 0.4216
                </li>
                <li>Compute 5 log<sub>10</sub>(d): 5 × 0.4216 ≈ 2.108</li>
                <li>Apply M = m − 5 log<sub>10</sub>(d) + 5:</li>
              </ol>
              <div class="formula-box font-mono text-sm">
                M ≈ −1.46 − 2.108 + 5 ≈ 1.43
              </div>
              <p>
                So Sirius has absolute magnitude M ≈ 1.4 – intrinsically
                brighter than the Sun (M<sub>☉</sub> ≈ 4.83).
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Distance from m and M</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose a star has apparent magnitude m = 10 and absolute
                magnitude M = 5. How far away is it?
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Compute m − M = 10 − 5 = 5</li>
                <li>Use d(pc) = 10<sup>(m − M + 5)/5</sup>:</li>
              </ol>
              <div class="formula-box font-mono text-sm">
                d = 10<sup>(5 + 5)/5</sup> = 10<sup>2</sup> = 100 pc
              </div>
              <p>100 pc ≈ 326 light-years.</p>

              <h3>Example 3 – Luminosity from absolute magnitude</h3>
              <p>
                Take a star with absolute magnitude M = 0. Using M<sub>☉</sub> =
                4.83:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box font-mono text-sm">
                L / L<sub>☉</sub> = 10<sup>(4.83 − 0)/2.5</sup> = 10<sup
                  >1.932</sup
                >
                ≈ 85
              </div>
              <p>This star is about 85 times more luminous than the Sun.</p>

              <h2>Common pitfalls & tips</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use parsecs in the distance modulus.</strong> If you
                  have light-years, convert first.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check your signs.</strong> More negative magnitudes
                  mean brighter objects.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use consistent bands.</strong> Compare magnitudes only
                  if they are in the same filter (e.g., V-band).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Extinction (dust) is ignored here.</strong> For
                  precise work, interstellar extinction A<sub>V</sub> must be
                  included.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">
                FAQ: Apparent vs Absolute Magnitude
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3">
                <details class="border rounded-md px-4 py-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is the difference between apparent and absolute
                    magnitude?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Apparent magnitude m is how bright an object appears from
                    Earth, combining its intrinsic luminosity and distance (and
                    extinction). Absolute magnitude M is how bright it would
                    appear if placed at 10 parsecs. M is therefore a measure of
                    intrinsic power output, independent of distance.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border rounded-md px-4 py-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Why do brighter objects have smaller or negative magnitudes?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The magnitude system is historical and logarithmic. It was
                    defined so that a difference of 5 magnitudes corresponds to
                    a factor of 100 in brightness, and the brightest stars known
                    to ancient astronomers were assigned small numbers.
                    Extending this scale naturally leads to zero and negative
                    values for extremely bright objects like the Sun or Venus.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border rounded-md px-4 py-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What distance unit should I use in the distance modulus?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The standard distance modulus uses distance in
                    <strong>parsecs</strong>. If your distance is in
                    light-years, convert using 1 pc ≈ 3.26156 ly. The calculator
                    lets you choose either unit and converts internally to
                    parsecs for the formula.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border rounded-md px-4 py-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How accurate is this calculator for real astronomical data?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    For basic educational and observational astronomy, the
                    formulas used here are standard and accurate. Professional
                    work often includes additional effects such as interstellar
                    extinction, K-corrections for redshift, and
                    bandpass-specific calibrations, which are beyond the scope
                    of this simple tool.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border rounded-md px-4 py-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can I compare magnitudes from different filters (e.g., V vs
                    B)?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Not directly. Magnitudes are defined per filter band. To
                    compare intrinsic luminosities, you should use magnitudes in
                    the same band or convert to bolometric magnitudes using
                    appropriate corrections.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>
